No. There is no PyObjC-style bridge in Node/TypeScript.
	•	PyObjC works because Python can dynamically load Objective-C runtime symbols and expose Cocoa frameworks directly.
	•	Node.js does not have an equivalent out of the box. You cannot require("Cocoa") or call AXUIElementCopyAttributeValue directly.

Your options in TypeScript:
	1.	Native addon (N-API / node-ffi). Write a small C/Obj-C or Swift wrapper that calls the Accessibility API and exports functions to JS.
	2.	Spawn a helper. Call a Swift/Python program (like macapptree) from Node, parse its JSON.
	3.	JXA (JavaScript for Automation). Use osascript -l JavaScript to access System Events. This is slower and less complete, but avoids compiling anything.

So if you want PyObjC-level convenience in TypeScript, you must build it. There is no preexisting maintained package that binds the macOS Accessibility framework to Node.
How can Python do this with obj c in a way that node can’t

Python can do it because PyObjC is a full Objective-C runtime bridge. Node lacks such a bridge.

Key mechanics:
	•	Dynamic ObjC runtime access. PyObjC loads Cocoa frameworks, inspects classes and selectors via the Objective-C runtime, and dispatches calls through objc_msgSend at runtime. It maps ObjC objects to Python proxies and back.  ￼
	•	Type encoding + libffi. PyObjC parses Objective-C method signatures and uses libffi trampolines so Python can call methods with arbitrary argument and return types, including structs and pointers.  ￼

Why Node can’t do this “out of the box”:
	•	No built-in ObjC bridge. Node provides N-API for writing C/C++ addons, not a runtime bridge to Objective-C. You can build one, but it isn’t shipped.  ￼
	•	FFI libraries target the C ABI, not Objective-C messaging. Packages like ffi-napi let JS call plain C functions, but they don’t implement Objective-C message dispatch (objc_msgSend family), selector/type-encoding parsing, ARC/retain/release semantics, or blocks. You would need a custom addon to handle all of that.  ￼

What a Node equivalent would require:
	•	Import Objective-C metadata (selectors, type encodings), parse BridgeSupport-style info, wrap objc_msgSend variants, manage ARC and toll-free bridges (CoreFoundation/Foundation), integrate the Cocoa run loop, and expose proxies to JS. In short, reimplement PyObjC for Node.  ￼

Conclusion: Python “can” because PyObjC already implements the heavy bridge. Node “can’t” unless you write a native addon that replicates that functionality.
there's no node equivalent to pyobjc?

Correct. There is no Node.js equivalent to PyObjC.
	•	PyObjC is a maintained, full bridge from Python to the Objective-C runtime. It handles selectors, type encodings, objc_msgSend, CoreFoundation bridging, ARC, and blocks.
	•	Node has only C FFI libraries (ffi-napi, node-ffi, etc.). These call plain C functions but do not implement Objective-C’s messaging model. You cannot transparently import Cocoa frameworks or call selectors the way PyObjC does.
	•	A Node equivalent would need to wrap the ObjC runtime (objc_getClass, sel_registerName, objc_msgSend, etc.) and expose proxies to JS. No one has released and maintained such a bridge.

So today you have two paths in TypeScript:
	1.	Write a native addon (N-API/C++/Obj-C) that calls AX APIs directly.
	2.	Shell out to Swift or Python (PyObjC) tools and parse their JSON output.

There is no drop-in npm package that gives you what PyObjC does.

Yes, there is nodobjc, but it is unmaintained.
	•	It was an attempt at a PyObjC-style bridge for Node. It lets you call Objective-C classes and selectors from JS by wrapping the Objective-C runtime (objc_getClass, objc_msgSend, etc.).
	•	It was built on ffi and ref for Node. Those dependencies have since broken with modern Node versions, and the project has not been updated for years.
	•	People used it to call Cocoa APIs, but it is fragile, incomplete, and doesn’t support ARC, blocks, or modern frameworks well.

So: nodobjc exists, but it is effectively abandoned. If you want something reliable today, you will need to either:
	•	fork and modernize nodobjc (port to ffi-napi), or
	•	build your own N-API addon in C/ObjC, or
	•	spawn Python/Swift helpers and parse their output.
